16/AR2005121601559.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2014-02-28}}\n*{{cite news |title=Debating Evolution in the Classroom |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5014428 |work=[[National Public Radio|NPR]] |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=National Public Radio, Inc. |type=Story archive |accessdate=2014-02-28}}\n*{{cite news |last=Downey |first=Roger |date=February 1, 2006 |title=Discovery's Creation |url=http://www.seattleweekly.com/2006-02-01/news/discovery-s-creation/ |newspaper=[[Seattle Weekly]] |location=Phoenix, Ariz. |publisher=[[Village Voice Media]] |accessdate=2014-02-28 |ref=Downey 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305191048/http://www.seattleweekly.com/2006-02-01/news/discovery-s-creation/# |archive-date=2014-03-05 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite news |last1=Grier |first1=Peter |last2=Burek |first2=Josh |date=December 21, 2005 |title=Banned in biology class: intelligent design |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2005/1221/p01s01-ussc.html |work=[[Christian Science Monitor]] |accessdate=2014-02-28}}\n*{{cite episode |title=Judgment Day: Intelligent Design on Trial |episodelink=Judgment Day: Intelligent Design on Trial |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/evolution/intelligent-design-trial.html |accessdate=2014-02-28 |series=[[Nova (American TV series)|Nova]] |last1=Johnstone |first1=Gary (Director) |last2=McMaster |first2=Joseph (Director) |network=[[PBS]] |date=November 13, 2007 |season=35}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://ncse.com/news/2015/09/kitzmiller-york-daily-record-0016640 |title=Kitzmiller in the York Daily Record |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 11, 2015 |website=National Center for Science Education |publisher=National Center for Science Education |location=Berkeley, Calif. |accessdate=2015-10-22}}\n*{{cite news |last=Lemonick |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Lemonick |date=December 20, 2005 |title=Darwin Victorious |url=http://content.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1142672,00.html |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=2014-02-28}}\n*{{cite news |last=Orr |first=H. Allen |authorlink=H. Allen Orr |date=May 30, 2005 |title=Devolution |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/05/30/050530fa_fact |journal=[[The New Yorker]] |location=New York |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |accessdate=2014-02-28 |ref=Orr 2005}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{Featured article}}\n{{Creationism topics}}\n{{pseudoscience}}\n{{philosophy of religion}}\n{{God arguments}}\n{{Design}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Evolutionary biology|Science}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Intelligent Design}}\n[[Category:Intelligent design| ]]\n[[Category:Arguments for the existence of God]]\n[[Category:Creationist objections to evolution]]\n[[Category:Denialism]]\n", "name_user": "Rayner111", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligent_design"}
{"title_page": "Pat Eilers", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL player\n| name = \n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| number = 24, 25\n| position = [[Safety (American football position)|Safety]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|9|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lbs = 197\n| high_school = [[Saint Thomas Academy|Mendota Heights (MN) St. Thomas Academy]]\n| college = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| undraftedyear= 1990\n| pastteams =\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|1990}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1991}})\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1992}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1994}})\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ({{NFL Year|1995}})\n| statlabel1 = Games played\n| statvalue1 = 61\n| statlabel2 = Fumble recoveries\n| statvalue2 = 7\n| nfl = EIL415291\n| pfr = EilePa20\n}}\n'''Patrick Christopher Eilers''' (born September 3, 1966) is a former [[American football]] [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Washington Redskins]], and [[Chicago Bears]].  He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Notre Dame]] and was a member of the [[1988 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|1988 Fighting Irish team]], which won a [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national championship]].  \n\nHe graduated with degrees in [[biology]] and [[mechanical engineering]] in 1989 and 1990, respectively from Notre Dame.  Prior to attending Notre Dame, he spent his first year of university at [[Yale University|Yale]], where he was a member of the [[Yale Bulldogs football]] team.  Furthermore, after the end of his playing career in the NFL, he earned a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Northwestern University]]'s [[Kellogg School of Management]].<ref>http://www.ndinsider.com/football/former-notre-dame-football-player-and-wife-endow-coaching-position/article_c60e37b6-6eb0-11e5-8d81-831ce239478e.html</ref>\n\nEilers is currently a managing director within BlackRock's infrastructure Investment Group, and heads the firms corporate equity and special situation investments within the conventional power industry. Previously, Eilers served as a Managing Director of Madison Dearborn Partners, LLC and oversaw its energy, power and chemicals practice. Pat worked at Madison Dearborn Partners from 1999 to 2015.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=EIL415291 |ESPN= |cfl= |cbs= |si= |yahoo= |pfr=EilePa20 }}\n\n{{1988 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football navbox}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eilers, Pat}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football safeties]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins players]]\n[[Category:Madison Dearborn Partners]]\n[[Category:Private equity and venture capital investors]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Yale Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n\n\n{{defensiveback-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL player\n| name = \n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| number = 24, 25\n| position = [[Safety (American football position)|Safety]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|9|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lbs = 197\n| high_school = [[Saint Thomas Academy|Mendota Heights (MN) St. Thomas Academy]]\n| college = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]]\n| undraftedyear= 1990\n| pastteams =\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|1990}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1991}})\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1992}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1994}})\n* [[Chicago Bears]] ({{NFL Year|1995}})\n| statlabel1 = Games played\n| statvalue1 = 61\n| statlabel2 = Fumble recoveries\n| statvalue2 = 7\n| nfl = EIL415291\n| pfr = EilePa20\n}}\n'''Patrick Christopher Eilers''' (born September 3, 1966) is a former [[American football]] [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Washington Redskins]], and [[Chicago Bears]].  He played [[college football]] at the [[University of Notre Dame]] and was a member of the [[1988 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|1988 Fighting Irish team]], which won a [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national championship]].  \n\nHe graduated with degrees in [[biology]] and [[mechanical engineering]] in 1989 and 1990, respectively from Notre Dame.  Prior to attending Notre Dame, he spent his first year of university at [[Yale University|Yale]], where he was a member of the [[Yale Bulldogs football]] team.  Furthermore, after the end of his playing career in the NFL, he earned a [[Masters of Business Administration]] from [[Northwestern University]]'s [[Kellogg School of Management]].<ref>http://www.ndinsider.com/football/former-notre-dame-football-player-and-wife-endow-coaching-position/article_c60e37b6-6eb0-11e5-8d81-831ce239478e.html</ref>\n\nEilers is currently a managing director within BlackRock's infrastructure Investment Group, and heads the firms corporate equity and special situation investments within the conventional power industry. Previously, Eilers served as a Managing Director of Madison Dearborn Partners, LLC and oversaw its energy, power and chemicals practice. Pat worked at Madison Dearborn Partners from 1999 to 2015.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=EIL415291 |ESPN= |cfl= |cbs= |si= |yahoo= |pfr=EilePa20 }}\n\n{{1988 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football navbox}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eilers, Pat}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football safeties]]\n[[Category:Chicago Bears players]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Fighting Irish football players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins players]]\n[[Category:Madison Dearborn Partners]]\n[[Category:Private equity and venture capital investors]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Saint Paul, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Yale Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Notre Dame alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n\n\n{{defensiveback-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: Masters \u2192 Master", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pat_Eilers"}
{"title_page": "Compact Disk Dummies", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Compact Disk Dummies\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Desselgem]], Belgium\n| genre               = [[Electropunk]]\n| years_active        = 2010\u2013present\n| label               = [[PIAS Recordings|[PIAS] Recordings]]\n| website             = {{url|www.compactdiskdummies.info/}}\n| current_members     = [[Lennert Coorevits]]<br />[[Janus Coorevits]]\n| past_members        = \n}}\n\nThe '''Compact Disk Dummies''' is a Belgian [[electropunk]] band from [[Desselgem]] (Waregem). The group consists of the brothers Lennert (born in 1993) and Janus Coorevits (born in 1995). Both do the vocals and play [[synthesizer|keyboard]]s, Lennert also plays the guitar.\n\n== History ==\nThe group was founded in 2010 and in the same year they won the Music Live event,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeugdenmuziek.be/news/20/laatste-week-inschrijvingen-imagine |title=Laatste week inschrijvingen! |publisher=Jeugd en Muziek Vlaanderen |language=nl |accessdate=13 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213210141/http://www.jeugdenmuziek.be/news/20/laatste-week-inschrijvingen-imagine |archive-date=13 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and ended second at the Belgian edition of the [[Kunstbende]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kunstbende.be/historiek/#2010 |title=Historiek |publisher=Kunstbende |language=nl |accessdate=13 February 2015 }}</ref> Their musical breakthrough came when the two brothers won [[Humo's Rock Rally]] as teenagers in 2012, in the [[Ancienne Belgique]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20120325_116 |title=Compact Disk Dummies wint Rock Rally |language=nl |newspaper= [[Het Nieuwsblad]] |first=Sasha |last=Van der Speeten |date=25 March 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2015 }}</ref> They ended before groups as [[Geppetto & The Whales]] to become the successors of [[School is Cool]].\n\nIn March 2013 they brought out their first [[Extended play|EP]] \"Mess with Us\", together with their first single \"The Reeling\". The title temporarily reached the top of [[Studio Brussel]]'s [[De Afrekening]] list on 27 April 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/blkva_20130427_002 |title=FAZ: Compact Disk Dummies op 1 in De Afrekening van Studio Brussel |author=vhp |publisher=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |language=nl |date=27 April 2013 |accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> and stood in the Flemish [[Ultratop]] 50 during six weeks.<ref name=\"fl-s\" /> In the summer of 2013 they featured in festivals like the [[Lokerse Feesten]] and [[Pukkelpop]].\n\nOn 6 May 2016, the band released their debut album ''Silver Souls''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Compact-Disk-Dummies-Silver-Souls/release/8521809|title=Compact Disk Dummies \u2013 Silver Souls|publisher=discogs}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n=== Albums ===\n* ''Silver Souls'' (2016)\n\n=== Extended plays ===\n* ''Mess with Us'' (2013)\n* ''Satellites'' (2019)\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" width=\"10\"|Year\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" width=\"120\"|Single\n!align=\"center\" colspan=\"1\" width=\"20\"|Peak positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Ultratop|BEL <br>(Fl)]]<br><ref name=\"fl-s\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/search.asp?search=compact%20disk%20dummies&cat=s | title=Compact Disk Dummies | website=Ultratop.be/nl |accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|2013\n|\"The Reeling\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|38\n|-\n|\"Mess with Us\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip68\n|-\n|\"What You Want\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip14\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2016\n|\"Girls Keep Drinking\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip22\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2017\n|\"Remain in Light\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip43\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n|\"Cry for Me\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip13\n|-\n|\"Satellites\"<br />{{small|(featuring [[Tom Barman]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2020\n|\"I Remember\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip5\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.compactdiskdummies.info/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Belgian musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Rock music duos]]\n[[Category:Electropunk]]\n[[Category:PIAS Recordings artists]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Compact Disk Dummies\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Desselgem]], Belgium\n| genre               = [[Electropunk]]\n| years_active        = 2010\u2013present\n| label               = [[PIAS Recordings|[PIAS] Recordings]]\n| website             = {{url|www.compactdiskdummies.info/}}\n| current_members     = [[Lennert Coorevits]]<br />[[Janus Coorevits]]\n| past_members        = \n}}\n\nThe '''Compact Disk Dummies''' is a Belgian [[electropunk]] band from [[Desselgem]] (Waregem). The group consists of the brothers Lennert (born in 1993) and Janus Coorevits (born in 1995). Both do the vocals and play [[synthesizer|keyboard]]s, Lennert also plays the guitar.\n\n== History ==\nThe group was founded in 2010 and in the same year they won the Music Live event,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jeugdenmuziek.be/news/20/laatste-week-inschrijvingen-imagine |title=Laatste week inschrijvingen! |publisher=Jeugd en Muziek Vlaanderen |language=nl |accessdate=13 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213210141/http://www.jeugdenmuziek.be/news/20/laatste-week-inschrijvingen-imagine |archive-date=13 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and ended second at the Belgian edition of the [[Kunstbende]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kunstbende.be/historiek/#2010 |title=Historiek |publisher=Kunstbende |language=nl |accessdate=13 February 2015 }}</ref> Their musical breakthrough came when the two brothers won [[Humo's Rock Rally]] as teenagers in 2012, in the [[Ancienne Belgique]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20120325_116 |title=Compact Disk Dummies wint Rock Rally |language=nl |newspaper= [[Het Nieuwsblad]] |first=Sasha |last=Van der Speeten |date=25 March 2012 |accessdate=13 February 2015 }}</ref> They ended before groups as [[Geppetto & The Whales]] to become the successors of [[School is Cool]].\n\nIn March 2013 they brought out their first [[Extended play|EP]] \"Mess with Us\", together with their first single \"The Reeling\". The title temporarily reached the top of [[Studio Brussel]]'s [[De Afrekening]] list on 27 April 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/blkva_20130427_002 |title=FAZ: Compact Disk Dummies op 1 in De Afrekening van Studio Brussel |author=vhp |publisher=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |language=nl |date=27 April 2013 |accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> and stood in the Flemish [[Ultratop]] 50 during six weeks.<ref name=\"fl-s\" /> In the summer of 2013 they featured in festivals like the [[Lokerse Feesten]] and [[Pukkelpop]].\n\nOn 6 May 2016, the band released their debut album ''Silver Souls''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Compact-Disk-Dummies-Silver-Souls/release/8521809|title=Compact Disk Dummies \u2013 Silver Souls|publisher=discogs}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n=== Albums ===\n* ''Silver Souls'' (2016)\n\n=== Extended plays ===\n* ''Mess with Us'' (2013)\n* ''Satellites'' (2019)\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" width=\"10\"|Year\n!align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" width=\"120\"|Single\n!align=\"center\" colspan=\"1\" width=\"20\"|Peak positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:5em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Ultratop|BEL <br>(Fl)]]<br><ref name=\"fl-s\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/search.asp?search=compact%20disk%20dummies&cat=s | title=Compact Disk Dummies | website=Ultratop.be/nl |accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\"|2013\n|\"The Reeling\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|38\n|-\n|\"Mess with Us\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip68\n|-\n|\"What You Want\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip14\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2016\n|\"Girls Keep Drinking\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip22\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2017\n|\"Remain in Light\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip43\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n|\"Cry for Me\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip13\n|-\n|\"Satellites\"<br />{{small|(featuring [[Tom Barman]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2020\n|\"I Remember\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|tip6\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.compactdiskdummies.info/}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Belgian musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Rock music duos]]\n[[Category:Electropunk]]\n[[Category:PIAS Recordings artists]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-band-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSingles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_Disk_Dummies"}
{"title_page": "Georgia Davies", "text_new": "{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Georgia Davies\n| image          =\n| image_size     = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Georgia Davies of Great Britain competes in the Women's 100m Backstroke at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games \n| fullname       = Georgia Beth Davies\n| national_team  = Great Britan<br>Wales\n| strokes        = [[Backstroke]]\n| club           = Loughborough University\n| coach          = James Gibson\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1990|10|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[London]], England\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 1.75 m\n| weight         = 60 kg\n| medaltemplates =\n{{medalSport | Women's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry |{{GBR2}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 Gwangju]]|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FINA World Swimming Championships (25m)|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2016 Windsor]]|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[LEN European Aquatics Championships|European Championships (LC)]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold | [[2016 European Aquatics Championships|2016 London]] | [[Swimming at the 2016 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Mixed 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold | 2016 London | [[Swimming at the 2016 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold | [[2018 European Aquatics Championships|2018 Glasgow]] | [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2014 European Aquatics Championships|2014 Berlin]] | [[Swimming at the 2014 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver | 2018 Glasgow | [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2014 Berlin | [[Swimming at the 2014 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2014 Berlin | [[Swimming at the 2014 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4x100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze |2016 London | [[Swimming at the 2016 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze | 2018 Glasgow | [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013  Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[European Short Course Swimming Championships|European Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2011 European Short Course Swimming Championships|2011 Szczecin]] | 50 m backstroke}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 European Short Course Swimming Championships|2019 Glasgow]]|100 m backstroke}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{WAL}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]] | [[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2014 Glasgow | [[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 Delhi]] | [[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2018 Gold Coast | [[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n}}\n'''Georgia Beth Davies''' (born 11 October 1990) is a Welsh competition [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who has represented Great Britain in the Olympic Games and European championships, and swam for Wales in the Commonwealth Games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Georgia Davies |website=London2012.com |url=http://www.london2012.com/athlete/davies-georgia-1127164/ |url-status=dead |archivedate=15 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515161036/http://www.london2012.com/athlete/davies-georgia-1127164/ }}</ref>  She has won gold in the Commonwealth Games and European Championships.\n\n==Career==\n===Early career (2010-2012)===\nGeorgia Davies made her senior breakthrough as part of the Wales team at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]], entering 5 events.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/commonwealth_games/delhi_2010/9049695.stm|title=Commonwealth Games 2010: Swimming results|date=2010-09-30|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> She won a bronze medal in the 50 metre backstroke. She also made the finals in the 100 metre backstroke, where she finished 6th, the 4x100 metre medley relay, where she finished 4th and the 4x200 metre freestyle relay, where she finished 6th. She also competed in the 200 metre freestyle, finishing 15th.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/commonwealth_games/delhi_2010/9049695.stm|title=Commonwealth Games 2010: Swimming results|date=2010-09-30|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nShe competed for Team GB at the [[2011 World Aquatics Championships|2011 World Championships]], where she made the final as part of the 4x100 metre medley team, eventually finishing 6th. She also competed in the 50m backstroke, finishing 10th and missing out on the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishswimming.org/athlete-swimming-profiles/british-swimming-profiles/georgia-davies/|title=Georgia Davies|website=British Swimming|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> \n\nAt the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], she competed in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|women's 100-metre backstroke]], finishing 6th in the heats. However, she was eliminated in the semifinal in 15th position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/19047187|title=Georgia Davies saddened by semi-final performance|date=2012-07-30|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\n===Later career (2014-present)===\nGeorgia Davies competed in 2 events in the [[2013 World Aquatics Championships|2013 World Championships]], the 50 metre backstroke, where she made the final and finished 6th and the 100 metre backstroke, where she finished 19th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishswimming.org/athlete-swimming-profiles/british-swimming-profiles/georgia-davies/|title=Georgia Davies|website=British Swimming|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Davies won the gold medal in the 50 metre backstroke, and silver in the 100 metre backstroke at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]]. A month later, she won silver in the 50m backstroke and bronze in the 100-metre backstroke and 4\u00d7100-metre medley relay at the [[2014 European Aquatics Championships|2014 European Championships]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/other-sport/welsh-swimming-star-georgia-davies-8213521|title=Welsh swimming star Georgia Davies reaping the rewards as big decisions begin to pay off|last=Woolford|first=Anthony|date=2014-12-02|work=walesonline|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nShe represented Team GB again in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Summer Olympics]], where she competed in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 metre backstroke]] but again went out in the semifinals, finishing 10th.<ref>{{cite web|title=SWW041200_ResultsSummary_2016_08_07.pdf:|url=https://smsprio2016-a.akamaihd.net/_odf-documents/S/W/SWW041200_ResultsSummary_2016_08_07.pdf|publisher=Rio 2016|accessdate=8 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809145410/https://smsprio2016-a.akamaihd.net/_odf-documents/S/W/SWW041200_ResultsSummary_2016_08_07.pdf|archivedate=9 August 2016}}\n</ref> She made an olympic final as part of the 4x100 metre medley relay, finishing 7th.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.olympic.org/rio-2016/swimming/4x100m-medley-relay-women|title=Rio 2016 4x100m medley relay women - Olympic Swimming|date=2017-06-23|work=International Olympic Committee|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe won the bronze medal in the 100 metre backstroke at the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2014 World Championships (SC)]].\n\nAt the [[2011 World Aquatics Championships|2017 World Championships]], Davies made finals in the 4x100 metre medley relay and 50 metre backstroke, finishing 7th and 8th respectively. She also competed in the 100 metre backstroke, finishing 10th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishswimming.org/athlete-swimming-profiles/british-swimming-profiles/georgia-davies/|title=Georgia Davies|website=British Swimming|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nDavies represented Team Wales for the third time at the [[2018 Commonwealth Games]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://results.gc2018.com/en/swimming/athlete-profile-n6027943-georgia-davies.htm|title=Swimming {{!}} Athlete Profile: Georgia DAVIES - Gold Coast 2018 Commonwealth Games|website=results.gc2018.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> and Davies returned from Australia a double bronze medallist in the 50 metre backstroke<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games/43711682|title=Georgia Davies 'proud' to be on podium after winning bronze|date=2018-04-10|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> and 4x100 metre medley relay.\n\nAt the [[2018 European Aquatics Championships|2018 European Championships]], Davies won gold in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 metre backstroke]] finishing in 27.23 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/swimming/45075180 |title=European Championships 2018: Wales' Georgia Davies wins 50m backstroke gold|work=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2018 }}</ref>  She won another gold when she won as part of the team in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|mixed 4 \u00d7 100m medley]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/swimming/45084964 |title=European Championships 2018: Peaty, Anderson, Guy & Davies win mixed relay gold |work=BBC Sport |date=6 August 2018}}</ref> She added a silver in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 metre backstroke]],<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/swimming/45098510 |title=European Championships 2018: Ben Proud and Georgia Davies win silver medals |work=BBC Sport |date=7 August 2018}}</ref> and a bronze in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/more-sports/other-sports/news/29876/11467986/freya-anderson-wins-relay-bronze-to-end-european-swimming-championships |title=Freya Anderson wins relay bronze to end European Swimming Championships|first= Mark|last= Ashenden|date=9 August 2018 |work=Sky Sports }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 World Aquatics Championships]] held in [[Gwangju]], South Korea, Davies won a bronze as part of the British team in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed medley relay|4 \u00d7 100 m mixed medley relay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/av/swimming/49100596 |title=Watch: GB clinch bronze in 4x100m medley relay|date=24 July 2019 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n=== International Swimming League ===\nIn the Autumn of 2019 she was member of the inaugural [[International Swimming League]] swimming for the [[Energy Standard International Swim Club]], who won the team title in Las Vegas, Nevada, in December.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isl.global/club-rosters/|title=Club Rosters \u2013 International Swimming League|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FINA}}\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n\n{{Footer European Champions 4x100m Mixed Medley}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Georgia}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Welsh female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Female backstroke swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from London]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Swansea]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2014 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2018 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for Wales]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Wales]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for Wales]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ysgol Gyfun G\u0175yr]]\n[[Category:European Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox swimmer\n| name           = Georgia Davies\n| image          =\n| image_size     = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Georgia Davies of Great Britain competes in the Women's 100m Backstroke at the Rio 2016 Olympic Games \n| fullname       = Georgia Beth Davies\n| national_team  = Great Britan<br>Wales\n| strokes        = [[Backstroke]]\n| club           = Loughborough University\n| coach          = James Gibson\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1990|10|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[London]], England\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 1.75 m\n| weight         = 60 kg\n| medaltemplates =\n{{medalSport | Women's swimming}}\n{{MedalCountry |{{GBR2}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FINA World Aquatics Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 World Aquatics Championships|2019 Gwangju]]|[[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[FINA World Swimming Championships (25m)|World Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2016 Windsor]]|[[2016 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2018 Hangzhou]]|[[2018 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m) \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[LEN European Aquatics Championships|European Championships (LC)]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold | [[2016 European Aquatics Championships|2016 London]] | [[Swimming at the 2016 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Mixed 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold | 2016 London | [[Swimming at the 2016 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold | [[2018 European Aquatics Championships|2018 Glasgow]] | [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m mixed medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2014 European Aquatics Championships|2014 Berlin]] | [[Swimming at the 2014 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver | 2018 Glasgow | [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2014 Berlin | [[Swimming at the 2014 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2014 Berlin | [[Swimming at the 2014 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 x 100 metre medley relay|4x100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalBronze |2016 London | [[Swimming at the 2016 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze | 2018 Glasgow | [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013  Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[European Short Course Swimming Championships|European Championships (SC)]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2011 European Short Course Swimming Championships|2011 Szczecin]] | 50 m backstroke}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2019 European Short Course Swimming Championships|2019 Glasgow]]|100 m backstroke}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{WAL}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2014 Commonwealth Games|2014 Glasgow]] | [[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2014 Glasgow | [[Swimming at the 2014 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 Delhi]] | [[Swimming at the 2010 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 2018 Gold Coast | [[Swimming at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n}}\n'''Georgia Beth Davies''' (born 11 October 1990) is a Welsh competition [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who has represented Great Britain in the Olympic Games and European championships, and swam for Wales in the Commonwealth Games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Georgia Davies |website=London2012.com |url=http://www.london2012.com/athlete/davies-georgia-1127164/ |url-status=dead |archivedate=15 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515161036/http://www.london2012.com/athlete/davies-georgia-1127164/ }}</ref>  She has won gold in the Commonwealth Games and European Championships.\n\n==Career==\n===Early career (2010-2012)===\nGeorgia Davies made her senior breakthrough as part of the Wales team at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]], entering 5 events.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/commonwealth_games/delhi_2010/9049695.stm|title=Commonwealth Games 2010: Swimming results|date=2010-09-30|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> She won a bronze medal in the 50 metre backstroke. She also made the finals in the 100 metre backstroke, where she finished 6th, the 4x100 metre medley relay, where she finished 4th and the 4x200 metre freestyle relay, where she finished 6th. She also competed in the 200 metre freestyle, finishing 15th.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/commonwealth_games/delhi_2010/9049695.stm|title=Commonwealth Games 2010: Swimming results|date=2010-09-30|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nShe competed for Team GB at the [[2011 World Aquatics Championships|2011 World Championships]], where she made the final as part of the 4x100 metre medley team, eventually finishing 6th. She also competed in the 50m backstroke, finishing 10th and missing out on the final.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishswimming.org/athlete-swimming-profiles/british-swimming-profiles/georgia-davies/|title=Georgia Davies|website=British Swimming|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> \n\nAt the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], she competed in the [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|women's 100-metre backstroke]], finishing 6th in the heats. However, she was eliminated in the semifinal in 15th position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/19047187|title=Georgia Davies saddened by semi-final performance|date=2012-07-30|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\n===Later career (2014-present)===\nGeorgia Davies competed in 2 events in the [[2013 World Aquatics Championships|2013 World Championships]], the 50 metre backstroke, where she made the final and finished 6th and the 100 metre backstroke, where she finished 19th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishswimming.org/athlete-swimming-profiles/british-swimming-profiles/georgia-davies/|title=Georgia Davies|website=British Swimming|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Davies won the gold medal in the 50 metre backstroke, and silver in the 100 metre backstroke at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]]. A month later, she won silver in the 50m backstroke and bronze in the 100-metre backstroke and 4\u00d7100-metre medley relay at the [[2014 European Aquatics Championships|2014 European Championships]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/other-sport/welsh-swimming-star-georgia-davies-8213521|title=Welsh swimming star Georgia Davies reaping the rewards as big decisions begin to pay off|last=Woolford|first=Anthony|date=2014-12-02|work=walesonline|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nShe represented Team GB again in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Summer Olympics]], where she competed in the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 metre backstroke]] but again went out in the semifinals, finishing 10th.<ref>{{cite web|title=SWW041200_ResultsSummary_2016_08_07.pdf:|url=https://smsprio2016-a.akamaihd.net/_odf-documents/S/W/SWW041200_ResultsSummary_2016_08_07.pdf|publisher=Rio 2016|accessdate=8 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809145410/https://smsprio2016-a.akamaihd.net/_odf-documents/S/W/SWW041200_ResultsSummary_2016_08_07.pdf|archivedate=9 August 2016}}\n</ref> She made an olympic final as part of the 4x100 metre medley relay, finishing 7th.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.olympic.org/rio-2016/swimming/4x100m-medley-relay-women|title=Rio 2016 4x100m medley relay women - Olympic Swimming|date=2017-06-23|work=International Olympic Committee|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe won the bronze medal in the 100 metre backstroke at the [[2014 FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)|2014 World Championships (SC)]].\n\nAt the [[2011 World Aquatics Championships|2017 World Championships]], Davies made finals in the 4x100 metre medley relay and 50 metre backstroke, finishing 7th and 8th respectively. She also competed in the 100 metre backstroke, finishing 10th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishswimming.org/athlete-swimming-profiles/british-swimming-profiles/georgia-davies/|title=Georgia Davies|website=British Swimming|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\nDavies represented Team Wales for the third time at the [[2018 Commonwealth Games]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://results.gc2018.com/en/swimming/athlete-profile-n6027943-georgia-davies.htm|title=Swimming {{!}} Athlete Profile: Georgia DAVIES - Gold Coast 2018 Commonwealth Games|website=results.gc2018.com|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> and Davies returned from Australia a double bronze medallist in the 50 metre backstroke<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games/43711682|title=Georgia Davies 'proud' to be on podium after winning bronze|date=2018-04-10|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref> and 4x100 metre medley relay.\n\nAt the [[2018 European Aquatics Championships|2018 European Championships]], Davies won gold in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 50 metre backstroke|50 metre backstroke]] finishing in 27.23 seconds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/swimming/45075180 |title=European Championships 2018: Wales' Georgia Davies wins 50m backstroke gold|work=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2018 }}</ref>  She won another gold when she won as part of the team in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Mixed 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|mixed 4 \u00d7 100m medley]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/swimming/45084964 |title=European Championships 2018: Peaty, Anderson, Guy & Davies win mixed relay gold |work=BBC Sport |date=6 August 2018}}</ref> She added a silver in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 100 metre backstroke|100 metre backstroke]],<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/swimming/45098510 |title=European Championships 2018: Ben Proud and Georgia Davies win silver medals |work=BBC Sport |date=7 August 2018}}</ref> and a bronze in the [[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|women's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/more-sports/other-sports/news/29876/11467986/freya-anderson-wins-relay-bronze-to-end-european-swimming-championships |title=Freya Anderson wins relay bronze to end European Swimming Championships|first= Mark|last= Ashenden|date=9 August 2018 |work=Sky Sports }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 World Aquatics Championships]] held in [[Gwangju]], South Korea, Davies won a bronze as part of the British team in the [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 4 \u00d7 100 metre mixed medley relay|4 \u00d7 100 m mixed medley relay]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/av/swimming/49100596 |title=Watch: GB clinch bronze in 4x100m medley relay|date=24 July 2019 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FINA}}\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n\n{{Footer European Champions 4x100m Mixed Medley}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Georgia}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Welsh female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Female backstroke swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from London]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Swansea]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2014 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2018 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games gold medallists for Wales]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Wales]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for Wales]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the FINA World Swimming Championships (25 m)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ysgol Gyfun G\u0175yr]]\n[[Category:European Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n", "name_user": "Coach Rushton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added International Swimming League section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgia_Davies"}
{"title_page": "Simon Birmingham", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix= [[Senator]] [[The Honourable]]\n| name            = Simon Birmingham\n| honorific-suffix= \n| image           = Simon Birmingham.jpg\n| size            =\n| caption         =\n\n| office          = [[Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment]]\n| primeminister    = [[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor     = [[Steven Ciobo]]\n| successor       = \n| term_start      = 28 August 2018\n| term_end        =\n| office1 = [[Leader of the Government in the Senate (Australia)|Deputy Senate Government Leader]]\n| term_start1 = 28 August 2018\n| term_end1 =\n| primeminister1 =[[Scott Morrison]]\n| leader1 = [[Mathias Cormann]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Mitch Fifield]]\n| successor1 = \n| office3          = [[Minister for Education and Training]]\n| primeminister3    = [[Malcolm Turnbull]]<br/>[[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor3     = [[Christopher Pyne]]\n| successor3       = [[Dan Tehan]] \n| term_start3      = 21 September 2015\n| term_end3        = 28 August 2018\n| office4          = [[Minister for Education and Training#List of assistant ministers|Assistant Minister for Education and Training]]\n|primeminister4    = [[Tony Abbott]]<br />[[Malcolm Turnbull]]\n| predecessor4     = [[Sussan Ley]]\n| successor4      = ''Office abolished''\n| term_start4      = 23 December 2014\n| term_end4        = 21 September 2015\n| office5         = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[South Australia]]\n| term_start5     = 3 May 2007\n| term_end5       = \n| predecessor5    = [[Jeannie Ferris]]\n| successor5      = \n| birth_name = Simon John Birmingham\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1974|06|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Ashford, South Australia|Ashford]], [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Senators_Interests/CitizenshipRegister |title=Citizenship Register |publisher=Parliament of Australia |accessdate=5 December 2017}}</ref>\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| nationality     = [[Australia]]n\n| party           = [[Liberal Party of Australia]]\n| spouse          = Courtney Morcombe\n| relations       = \n| children        = 2\n| residence       =\n| alma_mater      = [[University of Adelaide]]\n| occupation      =\n| profession      =\n| signature       =\n| website         = {{URL|www.senatorbirmingham.com.au/|senatorbirmingham.com.au}}\n| footnotes       =\n}}\n'''Simon John Birmingham''' (born 14 June 1974) is an Australian politician who has served as a [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[South Australia]] since 2007. He is a member of the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] and has been [[Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment]] in the [[Morrison Government]] since 2018. He previously served as [[Minister for Education and Training]] in the [[Turnbull Government]] from 2015 to 2018, and as a [[parliamentary secretary]] and [[assistant minister]] in the [[Abbott Government]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBirmingham grew up on his family's horse [[agistment]] property near [[Gawler, South Australia]].<ref name=bio>{{cite news|url=https://www.senatorbirmingham.com.au/about-simon/biography/|title=Biography|publisher=Simon Birmingham|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Gawler High School]] and the [[University of Adelaide]]; neither of his parents had attended university. He has cited his grandmother Madge Herde, a school principal, as a key influence in his decision to enter politics.<ref name=dodd>{{cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/policy/health-and-education/simon-birmingham-the-man-behind-the-stunning-political-strike-which-revived-gonski-school-funding-20170503-gvy4xj|title=Simon Birmingham: The man behind Turnbull's stunning Gonski political strike|newspaper=[[The Australian Financial Review]]|date=5 May 2017|access-date=15 January 2020|first=Tim|last=Dodd}}</ref>\n\nBirmingham was named South Australia's [[Lions Club]] Youth of the Year in 1992<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lionsclubs.org.au/yoty/shr%20sa%20nt.htm |title=South Australia: Lions Club Youth of the Year |publisher=Lions Clubs of Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080722120358/http://lionsclubs.org.au/yoty/shr%20sa%20nt.htm |archivedate=22 July 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> and awarded the Town of [[Gawler]]'s Australia Day Young Citizen of the Year Award in 1993. He holds a [[Master of Business Administration]] from the Adelaide Graduate School of Business, [[University of Adelaide]].<ref name=Senbiog>{{cite web|url=http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/TranslateWIPILink.aspx?Folder=biogs&Criteria=NAME_ID:H6X%3B|title=Senator Simon John Birmingham|work=Members and Senators|publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090515023257/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/TranslateWIPILink.aspx?Folder=biogs&Criteria=NAME_ID:H6X;|archivedate=15 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe began his career working as an electorate officer for Senator [[Robert Hill (Australian ambassador)|Robert Hill]]. In 1997 Birmingham moved from federal to state politics, working as a ministerial advisor to [[Joan Hall]].\n\nEarly in 2000 Birmingham moved to [[Canberra]] to become the national manager of public affairs for the [[Australian Hotels Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/TranslateWIPILink.aspx?Folder=PRESSCLP&Criteria=CITATION_ID:SZ436%3B|title=Building industry tips job losses|work=[[The Age]]|date=4 January 2001}}{{dead link|date=November 2014}}</ref> In late 2001, Birmingham was appointed chief of staff to the South Australian state minister for tourism and innovation, [[Martin Hamilton-Smith]]. Following a change of government in 2002, Birmingham began work with the Winemakers' Federation of Australia where he remained until his appointment to the Senate in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/qanda/senators/birmingham.htm|title=Simon BirninghamP profile|work=[[Q&A (Australian talk show)|Q&A]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAt the age of 29, Birmingham won Liberal Party preselection for the marginal seat of [[Division of Hindmarsh|Hindmarsh]] at the [[2004 Australian federal election|2004 federal election]] following the retirement of sitting member [[Chris Gallus]]. The seat was narrowly won by [[Australian Labor Party|Labor's]] [[Steve Georganas]].<ref>Australian Electoral Commission, S.A Division\u2014Hindmarsh, 2004 election tally</ref>\n\nAfter an unsuccessful attempt to fill the vacancy created by Robert Hill's retirement from the Senate in 2006, Birmingham won Liberal Party preselection as a Senate candidate in [[Australian Federal Election, 2007|2007 federal election]] and was elected for a six-year term. However, he entered the Senate earlier, being appointed to fill the vacancy caused by the death of Senator [[Jeannie Ferris]].<ref name=Senbiog/> At the time of his appointment on 3 May 2007, Birmingham was the youngest member of the Australian Senate. He is identified with the moderate wing of the Liberal Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,18778684-2702,00.html|title=Loss for Hill's faction in Senate|work=[[The Australian]]|date=11 April 2006}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBirmingham served on Senate Environment, Communications, and Arts Committees from May 2007 to February 2010, the Senate Select Committee on the National Broadband Network as well as the [[Joint Standing Committee on Treaties]] from 2007 to September 2012. He was also the Chair of the Senate Environment and Communications References Committee (from September 2012), the Deputy Chair of the Senate Environment and Communications Legislation Committee (from September 2012), a member of the Joint Standing Committee on Electoral Matters (from February 2008) and a member of the Joint Committee on the National Broadband Network (from March 2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22handbook%2Fallmps%2FH6X%22|title=Biography for BIRMINGHAM, the Hon. Simon John|work=Senators and Members|publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]]}}</ref>\n\nBirmingham is also deputy chair of the Parliamentary Association for [[UNICEF]]. Birmingham has a keen interest in water issues including the health and future of the [[Murray Darling Basin]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independentweekly.com.au/news/local/news/general/victoria-slurps-murray-as-sa-dams/1489312.aspx|title=Victoria Slurps Murray as SA Dams|work=The Independent Weekly|date=18 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://parlinfo/parlInfo/download/media/pressclp/SG9R6/upload_binary/sg9r60.pdf;fileType=application/pdf#search=%22Advertiser%20Birmingham%20murray%22|title=Opinion: Government giving up on our Lower Lakes|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|date=14 August 2008}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://parlinfo/parlInfo/download/media/pressclp/37IP6/upload_binary/37ip63.pdf;fileType=application/pdf#search=%22Advertiser%20Birmingham%20murray%22|title=Lack of action is leaving us high and dry|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|date=25 January 2008}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in December 2008 introduced a Private Member's Bill, ''The Water Amendment (Saving the Goulburn and Murray Rivers) Bill 2008''. In December 2009 Birmingham was appointed to the Coalition frontbench as Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for the Murray Darling Basin and Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for Climate Action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberal.org.au/news.php?Id=4282|title=A Reshaped Coalition Team for Australia's Future|publisher=[[Liberal Party of Australia]]|date=8 December 2009}}</ref> After the 2010 election he was re-appointed Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for the Murray Darling Basin and appointed Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for the Environment. He also represented the Shadow Minister for Communications and Broadband, Hon [[Malcolm Turnbull]], in the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aph.gov.au/Library/parl/43/Shadow/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917122739/http://www.aph.gov.au/Library/parl/43/Shadow/index.htm |archivedate=17 September 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Ministerial appointments ===\n[[File:IA CEPA Signing Ceremony (47276317981).jpg|thumb|right|Birmingham and his Indonesian counterpart [[Enggartiasto Lukita]] at the signing of the Indonesia\u2013Australia Comprehensive Economic Partnership Agreement in March 2019]]\n{{further|Abbott Government|Turnbull Government|Turnbull Government}}\nFollowing the [[2013 Australian federal election|2013 federal election]], Birmingham served in the [[Abbott Ministry]] as a [[parliamentary secretary]] to the [[Minister for the Environment (Australia)|Minister for the Environment]] and from September 2013 until December 2014;<ref name=dpmc>{{cite web|url=http://www.dpmc.gov.au/parliamentary/docs/ministry_list_20130918.pdf |title=Abbott Ministry |work=[[Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet (Australia)|Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet]] |publisher=[[Commonwealth of Australia]] |date=18 September 2013 |accessdate=22 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926165842/http://www.dpmc.gov.au/parliamentary/docs/ministry_list_20130918.pdf |archivedate=26 September 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> when he was appointed as the [[Minister for Education and Training#List of assistant ministers|Assistant Minister for Education and Training]].<ref name=\"sworn\">{{cite news|title=Tony Abbott's revamped Ministry sworn in at Government House|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/tony-abbotts-revamped-ministry-sworn-in-at-government-house/story-fncynjr2-1227164880085|work=news.com.au|publisher=[[News Corp Australia]]|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"reshuffle2014-3\">{{cite news|title=Tony Abbott cabinet reshuffle moves Scott Morrison out of immigration|date=21 December 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2014/dec/21/tony-abbott-cabinet-reshuffle-moves-scott-morrison-out-of-immigration|author=Taylor, Lenore|work=[[Guardian Australia]]}}</ref> He became the Minister for Education and Training in the [[First Turnbull Ministry]] following the [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, September 2015]]. Upon the installment of the Morrison Ministry in August 2018, he became the Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment.\n\n==Political views==\nBirmingham is a member of the moderate or liberal wing of the Liberal Party, and was regarded as a key backer of Malcolm Turnbull in the [[September 2015 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill|2015 leadership contest]].<ref name=dodd/> According to Andrew Tillett, writing in ''[[The Australian Financial Review]]'' in August 2019, the retirement of [[Christopher Pyne]] saw Birmingham \"assume the mantle as the most senior moderate\" in the party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/the-rise-of-the-next-generation-of-factional-leaders-20190822-p52joy|title=The rise of the next generation of factional leaders|newspaper=[[The Australian Financial Reviews]]|date=23 August 2019|access-date=15 January 2020|first=Andrew|last=Tillett}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBirmingham is married to his former campaign manager Courtney Morcombe, who is the chief of staff to South Australian premier [[Steven Marshall]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/sa-weekend/a-liberal-dose-of-influence-for-adelaides-ultimate-power-couple-simon-birmingham-and-courtney-morcombe/news-story/51caa742266b2098f8086335d1160eeb|title=Simon Birmingham and Courtney Morcombe: Adelaide's ultimate power couple|newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|date=25 October 2019|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref> The couple has two daughters.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn a 2013 survey of Australian federal politics, Birmingham was one of only four MPs and senators to publicly identify as atheist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/do-australian-mps-believe-in-god/news-story/105d104df51b77ee48a5af05fe5bcba2|title=Do Australian MPs believe in God?|publisher=[[News.com.au]]|date=31 March 2013|access-date=15 January 2020|first=Candace|last=Sutton}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.senatorbirmingham.com.au Senator Birmingham's Official Website]\n*[http://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=H6X Australian Senate biography]\n*[https://theyvoteforyou.org.au/people/senate/sa/simon_birmingham Summary of parliamentary voting for Senator Simon Birmingham on TheyVoteForYou.org.au]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeannie Ferris]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[South Australia]]|years=2007\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sussan Ley]]|as=Assistant Minister for Education}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Education and Training#List of assistant ministers|Assistant Minister for Education and Training]] | years= 2014\u20132015 }}\n{{s-non|reason=Ministry abolished }}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Christopher Pyne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Education and Training]]|years=2015\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dan Tehan]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steven Ciobo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Australian Senators}}\n{{Australian Cabinet}}\n{{Abbott Ministry}}\n{{First Turnbull Ministry}}\n{{Second Turnbull Ministry}}\n{{First Morrison Ministry}}\n{{Second Morrison Ministry}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birmingham, Simon}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Abbott Government]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for South Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Turnbull Government]]\n[[Category:University of Adelaide alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Morrison Government]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix= [[Senator]] [[The Honourable]]\n| name            = Simon Birmingham\n| honorific-suffix= \n| image           = Simon Birmingham.jpg\n| size            =\n| caption         =\n\n| office          = [[Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment]]\n| primeminister    = [[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor     = [[Steven Ciobo]]\n| successor       = \n| term_start      = 28 August 2018\n| term_end        =\n| office1 = [[Leader of the Government in the Senate (Australia)|Deputy Senate Government Leader]]\n| term_start1 = 28 August 2018\n| term_end1 =\n| primeminister1 =[[Scott Morrison]]\n| leader1 = [[Mathias Cormann]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Mitch Fifield]]\n| successor1 = \n| office3          = [[Minister for Education and Training]]\n| primeminister3    = [[Malcolm Turnbull]]<br/>[[Scott Morrison]]\n| predecessor3     = [[Christopher Pyne]]\n| successor3       = [[Dan Tehan]] \n| term_start3      = 21 September 2015\n| term_end3        = 28 August 2018\n| office4          = [[Minister for Education and Training#List of assistant ministers|Assistant Minister for Education and Training]]\n|primeminister4    = [[Tony Abbott]]<br />[[Malcolm Turnbull]]\n| predecessor4     = [[Sussan Ley]]\n| successor4      = ''Office abolished''\n| term_start4      = 23 December 2014\n| term_end4        = 21 September 2015\n| office5         = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[South Australia]]\n| term_start5     = 3 May 2007\n| term_end5       = \n| predecessor5    = [[Jeannie Ferris]]\n| successor5      = \n| birth_name = Simon John Birmingham\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1974|06|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Ashford, South Australia|Ashford]], [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Senators_Interests/CitizenshipRegister |title=Citizenship Register |publisher=Parliament of Australia |accessdate=5 December 2017}}</ref>\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| nationality     = [[Australia]]n\n| party           = [[Liberal Party of Australia]]\n| spouse          = Courtney Morcombe\n| relations       = \n| children        = 2\n| residence       =\n| alma_mater      = [[University of Adelaide]]\n| occupation      =\n| profession      =\n| signature       =\n| website         = {{URL|www.senatorbirmingham.com.au/|senatorbirmingham.com.au}}\n| footnotes       =\n}}\n'''Simon John Birmingham''' (born 14 June 1974) is an Australian politician who has served as a [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[South Australia]] since 2007. He is a member of the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] and has been [[Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment]] in the [[Morrison Government]] since 2018. He previously served as [[Minister for Education and Training]] in the [[Turnbull Government]] from 2015 to 2018, and as a [[parliamentary secretary]] and [[assistant minister]] in the [[Abbott Government]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBirmingham grew up on his family's horse [[agistment]] property near [[Gawler, South Australia]].<ref name=bio>{{cite news|url=https://www.senatorbirmingham.com.au/about-simon/biography/|title=Biography|publisher=Simon Birmingham|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Gawler High School]] and the [[University of Adelaide]]; neither of his parents had attended university. He has cited his grandmother Madge Herde, a school principal, as a key influence in his decision to enter politics.<ref name=dodd>{{cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/policy/health-and-education/simon-birmingham-the-man-behind-the-stunning-political-strike-which-revived-gonski-school-funding-20170503-gvy4xj|title=Simon Birmingham: The man behind Turnbull's stunning Gonski political strike|newspaper=[[The Australian Financial Review]]|date=5 May 2017|access-date=15 January 2020|first=Tim|last=Dodd}}</ref>\n\nBirmingham was named South Australia's [[Lions Club]] Youth of the Year in 1992<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lionsclubs.org.au/yoty/shr%20sa%20nt.htm |title=South Australia: Lions Club Youth of the Year |publisher=Lions Clubs of Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080722120358/http://lionsclubs.org.au/yoty/shr%20sa%20nt.htm |archivedate=22 July 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> and awarded the Town of [[Gawler]]'s Australia Day Young Citizen of the Year Award in 1993. He holds a [[Masters of Business Administration]] from the Adelaide Graduate School of Business, [[University of Adelaide]].<ref name=Senbiog>{{cite web|url=http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/TranslateWIPILink.aspx?Folder=biogs&Criteria=NAME_ID:H6X%3B|title=Senator Simon John Birmingham|work=Members and Senators|publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090515023257/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/TranslateWIPILink.aspx?Folder=biogs&Criteria=NAME_ID:H6X;|archivedate=15 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe began his career working as an electorate officer for Senator [[Robert Hill (Australian ambassador)|Robert Hill]]. In 1997 Birmingham moved from federal to state politics, working as a ministerial advisor to [[Joan Hall]].\n\nEarly in 2000 Birmingham moved to [[Canberra]] to become the national manager of public affairs for the [[Australian Hotels Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/TranslateWIPILink.aspx?Folder=PRESSCLP&Criteria=CITATION_ID:SZ436%3B|title=Building industry tips job losses|work=[[The Age]]|date=4 January 2001}}{{dead link|date=November 2014}}</ref> In late 2001, Birmingham was appointed chief of staff to the South Australian state minister for tourism and innovation, [[Martin Hamilton-Smith]]. Following a change of government in 2002, Birmingham began work with the Winemakers' Federation of Australia where he remained until his appointment to the Senate in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/qanda/senators/birmingham.htm|title=Simon BirninghamP profile|work=[[Q&A (Australian talk show)|Q&A]]|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nAt the age of 29, Birmingham won Liberal Party preselection for the marginal seat of [[Division of Hindmarsh|Hindmarsh]] at the [[2004 Australian federal election|2004 federal election]] following the retirement of sitting member [[Chris Gallus]]. The seat was narrowly won by [[Australian Labor Party|Labor's]] [[Steve Georganas]].<ref>Australian Electoral Commission, S.A Division\u2014Hindmarsh, 2004 election tally</ref>\n\nAfter an unsuccessful attempt to fill the vacancy created by Robert Hill's retirement from the Senate in 2006, Birmingham won Liberal Party preselection as a Senate candidate in [[Australian Federal Election, 2007|2007 federal election]] and was elected for a six-year term. However, he entered the Senate earlier, being appointed to fill the vacancy caused by the death of Senator [[Jeannie Ferris]].<ref name=Senbiog/> At the time of his appointment on 3 May 2007, Birmingham was the youngest member of the Australian Senate. He is identified with the moderate wing of the Liberal Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,18778684-2702,00.html|title=Loss for Hill's faction in Senate|work=[[The Australian]]|date=11 April 2006}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBirmingham served on Senate Environment, Communications, and Arts Committees from May 2007 to February 2010, the Senate Select Committee on the National Broadband Network as well as the [[Joint Standing Committee on Treaties]] from 2007 to September 2012. He was also the Chair of the Senate Environment and Communications References Committee (from September 2012), the Deputy Chair of the Senate Environment and Communications Legislation Committee (from September 2012), a member of the Joint Standing Committee on Electoral Matters (from February 2008) and a member of the Joint Committee on the National Broadband Network (from March 2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22handbook%2Fallmps%2FH6X%22|title=Biography for BIRMINGHAM, the Hon. Simon John|work=Senators and Members|publisher=[[Parliament of Australia]]}}</ref>\n\nBirmingham is also deputy chair of the Parliamentary Association for [[UNICEF]]. Birmingham has a keen interest in water issues including the health and future of the [[Murray Darling Basin]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independentweekly.com.au/news/local/news/general/victoria-slurps-murray-as-sa-dams/1489312.aspx|title=Victoria Slurps Murray as SA Dams|work=The Independent Weekly|date=18 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://parlinfo/parlInfo/download/media/pressclp/SG9R6/upload_binary/sg9r60.pdf;fileType=application/pdf#search=%22Advertiser%20Birmingham%20murray%22|title=Opinion: Government giving up on our Lower Lakes|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|date=14 August 2008}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://parlinfo/parlInfo/download/media/pressclp/37IP6/upload_binary/37ip63.pdf;fileType=application/pdf#search=%22Advertiser%20Birmingham%20murray%22|title=Lack of action is leaving us high and dry|work=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|date=25 January 2008}}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in December 2008 introduced a Private Member's Bill, ''The Water Amendment (Saving the Goulburn and Murray Rivers) Bill 2008''. In December 2009 Birmingham was appointed to the Coalition frontbench as Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for the Murray Darling Basin and Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for Climate Action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberal.org.au/news.php?Id=4282|title=A Reshaped Coalition Team for Australia's Future|publisher=[[Liberal Party of Australia]]|date=8 December 2009}}</ref> After the 2010 election he was re-appointed Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for the Murray Darling Basin and appointed Shadow Parliamentary Secretary for the Environment. He also represented the Shadow Minister for Communications and Broadband, Hon [[Malcolm Turnbull]], in the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aph.gov.au/Library/parl/43/Shadow/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-10-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917122739/http://www.aph.gov.au/Library/parl/43/Shadow/index.htm |archivedate=17 September 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Ministerial appointments ===\n[[File:IA CEPA Signing Ceremony (47276317981).jpg|thumb|right|Birmingham and his Indonesian counterpart [[Enggartiasto Lukita]] at the signing of the Indonesia\u2013Australia Comprehensive Economic Partnership Agreement in March 2019]]\n{{further|Abbott Government|Turnbull Government|Turnbull Government}}\nFollowing the [[2013 Australian federal election|2013 federal election]], Birmingham served in the [[Abbott Ministry]] as a [[parliamentary secretary]] to the [[Minister for the Environment (Australia)|Minister for the Environment]] and from September 2013 until December 2014;<ref name=dpmc>{{cite web|url=http://www.dpmc.gov.au/parliamentary/docs/ministry_list_20130918.pdf |title=Abbott Ministry |work=[[Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet (Australia)|Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet]] |publisher=[[Commonwealth of Australia]] |date=18 September 2013 |accessdate=22 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926165842/http://www.dpmc.gov.au/parliamentary/docs/ministry_list_20130918.pdf |archivedate=26 September 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> when he was appointed as the [[Minister for Education and Training#List of assistant ministers|Assistant Minister for Education and Training]].<ref name=\"sworn\">{{cite news|title=Tony Abbott's revamped Ministry sworn in at Government House|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/tony-abbotts-revamped-ministry-sworn-in-at-government-house/story-fncynjr2-1227164880085|work=news.com.au|publisher=[[News Corp Australia]]|date=23 December 2014|accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"reshuffle2014-3\">{{cite news|title=Tony Abbott cabinet reshuffle moves Scott Morrison out of immigration|date=21 December 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2014/dec/21/tony-abbott-cabinet-reshuffle-moves-scott-morrison-out-of-immigration|author=Taylor, Lenore|work=[[Guardian Australia]]}}</ref> He became the Minister for Education and Training in the [[First Turnbull Ministry]] following the [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, September 2015]]. Upon the installment of the Morrison Ministry in August 2018, he became the Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment.\n\n==Political views==\nBirmingham is a member of the moderate or liberal wing of the Liberal Party, and was regarded as a key backer of Malcolm Turnbull in the [[September 2015 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill|2015 leadership contest]].<ref name=dodd/> According to Andrew Tillett, writing in ''[[The Australian Financial Review]]'' in August 2019, the retirement of [[Christopher Pyne]] saw Birmingham \"assume the mantle as the most senior moderate\" in the party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/the-rise-of-the-next-generation-of-factional-leaders-20190822-p52joy|title=The rise of the next generation of factional leaders|newspaper=[[The Australian Financial Reviews]]|date=23 August 2019|access-date=15 January 2020|first=Andrew|last=Tillett}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBirmingham is married to his former campaign manager Courtney Morcombe, who is the chief of staff to South Australian premier [[Steven Marshall]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/sa-weekend/a-liberal-dose-of-influence-for-adelaides-ultimate-power-couple-simon-birmingham-and-courtney-morcombe/news-story/51caa742266b2098f8086335d1160eeb|title=Simon Birmingham and Courtney Morcombe: Adelaide's ultimate power couple|newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|date=25 October 2019|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref> The couple has two daughters.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn a 2013 survey of Australian federal politics, Birmingham was one of only four MPs and senators to publicly identify as atheist.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/do-australian-mps-believe-in-god/news-story/105d104df51b77ee48a5af05fe5bcba2|title=Do Australian MPs believe in God?|publisher=[[News.com.au]]|date=31 March 2013|access-date=15 January 2020|first=Candace|last=Sutton}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.senatorbirmingham.com.au Senator Birmingham's Official Website]\n*[http://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=H6X Australian Senate biography]\n*[https://theyvoteforyou.org.au/people/senate/sa/simon_birmingham Summary of parliamentary voting for Senator Simon Birmingham on TheyVoteForYou.org.au]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeannie Ferris]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[South Australia]]|years=2007\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sussan Ley]]|as=Assistant Minister for Education}} \n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Education and Training#List of assistant ministers|Assistant Minister for Education and Training]] | years= 2014\u20132015 }}\n{{s-non|reason=Ministry abolished }}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Christopher Pyne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Education and Training]]|years=2015\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dan Tehan]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steven Ciobo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Trade, Tourism and Investment]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Australian Senators}}\n{{Australian Cabinet}}\n{{Abbott Ministry}}\n{{First Turnbull Ministry}}\n{{Second Turnbull Ministry}}\n{{First Morrison Ministry}}\n{{Second Morrison Ministry}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Birmingham, Simon}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Abbott Government]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Australia]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for South Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Adelaide]]\n[[Category:Turnbull Government]]\n[[Category:University of Adelaide alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:Morrison Government]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and career:replaced: Masters \u2192 Master", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simon_Birmingham"}
{"title_page": "International College of the Cayman Islands", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=May 2012}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2008}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n| name              = International College of the Cayman Islands\n| native_name       = \n| image_size        = \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = \n| latin_name        = \n| motto             = \n| mottoeng          = \n| established       = {{Start date|1970}}\n| closed            = \n| type              = [[Private university]]\n| affiliation       =\n| endowment         = \n| rector            = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| chairman          = \n| chancellor        = \n| president         = [[Dr. Byron R. Coon]]\n| vice-president    = \n| superintendent    = \n| provost           = \n| vice_chancellor   = \n| principal         = \n| dean              = \n| head_label        = \n| head              = \n| academic_staff    = \n| administrative_staff   = \n| students          = 200-250 full and part time\n| undergrad         = \n| postgrad          = \n| doctoral          = \n| other             = \n| city              = [[Newlands, Grand Cayman|Newlands]]\n| state             = \n| province          = \n| country           = [[Cayman Islands]]\n| campus            = [[Rural area|Rural]]\n| former_names      = \n| free_label        = Radio station\n| free              = 101.1 [[ICCI-FM]]\n| athletics         = \n| colours           = Blue and Gold\n| sports            = \n| nickname          = \n| mascot            = \n| website           = {{URL|www.icci.edu.ky}}\n| logo              = \n| footnotes         = \n| image_name        = \n| coor              = \n| colors            = \n| affiliations      =  \n|}}\nThe '''International College of the Cayman Islands''' (ICCI) is an accredited non-profit, private, four-year independent institution of higher education which opened in the fall of 1970.  It is the oldest college in the Cayman Islands and is located in [[Newlands, Grand Cayman|Newlands]] in the district of [[Bodden Town (district)|Bodden Town]] on the island of [[Grand Cayman]].\n\n==Location==\nThe campus of ICCI is located in the central part of Grand Cayman in the rural community of Newlands, approximately seven miles east of [[George Town, Cayman Islands|George Town]].\n\n==Legal control==\n\nThe International College of the Cayman Islands is incorporated as a nonprofit guarantee company in the Cayman Islands to operate as a private, independent institution of higher education. It is also registered with and recognized by the Education Council of the Cayman Islands Government.\n\nThe school's property and buildings are held in the name of the college by a board of trustees. The board is responsible for the maintenance of college properties and formulates college policy.\n\n==Students==\n\nThe student to faculty ratio at the International College of the Cayman Islands is 11:1. Most classes have about 15 students.  Students come to ICCI from other Caribbean Islands and every continent in the world. The school awarded degrees to 54 students in January 2010 at its 37th annual commencement ceremony and 72 degrees two years later in January 2012 at the 39th annual commencement.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.caycompass.com/cgi-bin/CFPnews.cgi?ID=10388613 |title=Fifty\u2013four receive ICCI degrees |date=12 January 2010 |publisher=CayCompass.com |access-date=15 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728063416/http://www.caycompass.com/cgi-bin/CFPnews.cgi?ID=10388613 |archive-date=28 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caymancompass.com/2012/01/10/Local-college-hosts-graduation/|title=Local college hosts graduation - Cayman Compass|first=Stuart|last=Wilson|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014, there were 44 graduates with 46 degrees awarded: 18 associate degrees, 16 bachelor's degrees, five master's degrees in human resources and seven master's degrees in business administration.https://www.caymancompass.com/2015/09/25/icci-celebrates-45th-anniversary/ In 2017, forty-six ICCI students received degrees including 17 students who received bachelor of science degrees and 17 who earned associate degrees. https://www.caymancompass.com/2017/03/01/icci-grads-get-set-for-a-bright-future/\n\nThe student population in the fall quarter of 2011 was made up of 231 students from 17 different nations.<ref name=EnrolmentHike>{{cite news|url=http://www.compasscayman.com/caycompass/2010/08/16/ICCI-expecting-enrolment-hike/ |title=ICCI expecting enrolment hike |date=16 August 2010 |publisher=CayCompass.com }}</ref>\n\n==Academic profile==\n\nICCI offers Associate of Science, Bachelor of Science, Master of Science, and [[Master of Business Administration]] degrees.\n\n[[Associate degree]]s are offered in business, general studies, and office administration. Business students can choose among several concentrations, including Accounting, Banking, Broadcasting Management, Finance, Hotel and Tourism Management, and Information Systems.\n\nMajors for the Bachelor of Science degree are Business Administration, Human and Social Services, Liberal Studies, and Office Administration. Business students may choose concentrations in Accounting or Finance.\n\nThe Master of Science degree is offered in two areas: Human Resources and Education.\n\n==Accreditation==\n\nICCI is accredited by ASIC UK as a Premier Institution.  The International Accreditation Council for Business Education (IACBE) has accredited all of ICCI's business programs.\n\nThe Association of Chartered Certified Accountants (ACCA) has granted \u201cExemption Accreditation\u201d to the college. Exemption Accreditation means ICCI graduates are exempted from certain examination papers ordinarily required by the ACCA. ICCI is recognized by the Cayman Islands Education Council which gives credence to its degrees.  Caymanian students attending ICCI are eligible for participation in Cayman Islands Government Scholarship.\n\n==Memberships==\n*[[American Association of Collegiate Registrars and Admissions Officers]] (AACRAO)\n*[[American Council of Education]] (ACE)\n*[[American Library Association]] (ALA)\n*[[Cayman Islands Chamber of Commerce]] (CICC)\n*[[Institute of International Education]] (IIE)\n*[[Library and Information Resources Network]], Inc. (LIRN)\n*[[World Association for Christian Communication]] (WACC)\n\n==Recognitions==\n\n*Recognized by the Cayman Island's Education Council; Caymanian students eligible for participation in Cayman Islands Government Scholarship\n*ICCI is accredited by ASIC UK as a Premier Institution. https://www.asic.org.uk/\n*The International Accreditation Council for Business Education (IACBE) has accredited all of ICCI's business programs. http://iacbe.org/\n*The Association of Chartered Certified Accountants (ACCA) has granted \u201cExemption Accreditation\u201d to the college. Exemption Accreditation means ICCI graduates are exempted from certain examination papers ordinarily required by the ACCA. http://www.accaglobal.com/us/en.html, http://www.accaglobal.com/us/en/learning-provider/learningproviders-exemptions.html\n*Approved by the [[United States Veterans Administration]] as an institution of higher education for enrollment of eligible veterans\n*Approved by the British Chartered Institute of Bankers as an institution offering banking courses (The B.S. degree in business administration meets the requirements for admission to the Associate Chartered Institute of Bankers (ACIB) program.)\n*Approved by [[Educational Testing Services]] (ETS) for inclusion in the list of GMAT score recipients.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Cayman Islands}}\n{{Education in British Overseas Territories}}\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:International College Of The Cayman Islands}}\n[[Category:Colleges in the Cayman Islands]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1970]]\n", "text_old": "{